WEBVTT

00:10.466 --> 00:11.790
Hey everyone, great to see you.

00:12.091 --> 00:14.318
For those of you who don't know me yet, I'm Jeremy.

00:14.338 --> 00:18.772
I'm one of the pastors here at Reality LA and it's my joy to be able to preach the word to you.

00:19.253 --> 00:23.506
Before we get to that today though, I have a couple of things I want to talk with you about really quick.

00:23.618 --> 00:27.083
First of all, next Sunday is Easter Sunday.

00:27.383 --> 00:28.925
And I'm so excited for this.

00:29.005 --> 00:36.675
We have great plans for Easter and particularly for how to get the gospel out this year like we never have done before.

00:36.776 --> 00:37.617
Here's what we're going to do.

00:38.238 --> 00:48.531
We're asking everyone in the church as much as possible to be able to share a video of yourself, sharing your testimony, talking about how Jesus has changed your life.

00:48.972 --> 00:53.618
Put that on social media and use the hashtag, Jesus changed my life.

00:53.986 --> 01:04.709
And then we also want you to put reality LA's handle on there so that if they click on that it'll go to one of our social media pages and invite them to an online Easter service.

01:04.849 --> 01:08.477
Now this is an idea that I had and I thought this would be great for our church.

01:08.537 --> 01:13.487
I invited some other pastors in LA to join in on it and honestly it's just taken off.

01:13.588 --> 01:14.770
I mean we've got at least

01:14.882 --> 01:35.981
25 churches in LA that are doing this and then churches across the nation have have joined in from everywhere from Seattle to San Diego Detroit Atlanta New York City and last night I had the opportunity I was given a platform to be able to do a global invitation for churches all over the world to join in this So it's going to be incredible.

01:36.081 --> 01:38.706
We want you to start posting these videos and

01:38.786 --> 01:54.149
tomorrow on Monday and we'll have the whole week to just see the momentum build and to see people all over the world being able to see story after story after story of how Jesus has changed other people's lives and for them to know that the same thing can happen with them.

01:54.750 --> 02:02.962
And then on Easter Sunday we're going to have a special service that we'll be asking you to celebrate together with with your digital gatherings

02:03.074 --> 02:09.742
We're also gonna have a larger Zoom gathering that will be available to people who don't have community groups.

02:09.802 --> 02:14.067
That'll be at 11 o'clock and we'll have a Zoom link out for that.

02:14.848 --> 02:26.563
Okay, one other thing to talk about before we get to the preaching of the word is an important part of our worship is giving and giving of our ties and offerings to the Lord knowing that He has given so much to us.

02:27.263 --> 02:29.706
And I just wanna say mostly about this.

02:29.766 --> 02:32.690
I just wanna say thank you for your faithfulness and giving.

02:32.770 --> 02:38.797
and the way that you have joyfully and sacrificially shown your commitment to the Lord and to His church during this time.

02:38.837 --> 02:40.799
And I want to call us to keep doing that.

02:41.480 --> 02:43.302
The way to give is through push pay.

02:43.682 --> 02:44.323
It's an app.

02:44.343 --> 02:50.289
If you don't have that app on your phone yet, you can find that at the App Store, download it, search for reality LA.

02:50.710 --> 02:52.031
It's really easy to set up.

02:52.391 --> 03:02.002
And I want to call you to continue to give so that we can be a blessing to this city so that we can show God's love to our city in a time where a lot of people are really in need and hurting.

03:02.626 --> 03:04.708
Okay, if you've got a Bible, go ahead and grab it.

03:05.509 --> 03:07.892
Open it up to Matthew chapter 21.

03:09.093 --> 03:17.062
We've been talking over the last few weeks about our response to this global pandemic as being one of faith, hope and love.

03:17.583 --> 03:23.730
But this week and next week is going to be all about God's response to the pain and suffering of this world.

03:24.290 --> 03:26.052
And so this week is Palm Sunday.

03:26.092 --> 03:27.234
Today is Palm Sunday.

03:27.294 --> 03:31.218
This is the beginning of Holy Week leading up to Easter.

03:31.586 --> 03:36.911
And so I'm gonna be reading Matthew 21 verses one through 10.

03:37.011 --> 03:46.040
This is the story of the triumphal entry where Jesus comes into Jerusalem on the final week of his life before he then rises from the dead.

03:46.861 --> 03:52.105
And I'll read this passage, but then I'll also be walking through several passages that cover that final week.

03:52.206 --> 03:56.690
So I'll read the text for us out loud and then I'll open our time in prayer.

03:57.471 --> 04:01.074
Matthew chapter 21, verses one through 10.

04:02.626 --> 04:15.585
Now when they drew near to Jerusalem and came to Bethphage to the Mount of Olives, then Jesus sent two disciples saying to them, go into the village in front of you and immediately you will find a donkey tied and a cult with her.

04:16.266 --> 04:17.828
Untie them and bring them to me.

04:17.868 --> 04:23.496
If anyone says anything to you, you shall say the Lord needs them and he will send them at once.

04:24.277 --> 04:30.386
This took place to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet saying, say to the daughter of Zion, behold,

04:30.498 --> 04:37.447
Your king is coming to you, humble and mounted on a donkey on a colt, the full of a beast of burden.

04:38.308 --> 04:41.012
The disciples went and did as Jesus had directed them.

04:41.712 --> 04:45.798
They brought the donkey and the colt and put on them their cloaks and he sat on them.

04:46.679 --> 04:52.306
Most of the crowds spread their cloaks on the road and others cut branches from the trees and spread them on the road.

04:52.706 --> 05:03.360
and the crowds that went before him and that followed him were shouting, Hosanna to the son of David, blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord, Hosanna in the highest.

05:04.301 --> 05:10.549
And when he entered Jerusalem, the whole city was stirred up saying, who is this?

05:11.450 --> 05:12.291
This is God's word.

05:12.732 --> 05:13.493
Let's pray together.

05:15.856 --> 05:20.722
Lord, we come before you in a time where there's a lot of uncertainty, a lot of confusion,

05:21.378 --> 05:22.660
A lot of distraction.

05:22.680 --> 05:31.673
And we pray, Lord, through the preaching of your word, that we would have clarity on who your son Jesus Christ is and what he's done for us.

05:32.694 --> 05:41.246
Lord, as we begin this holy week, we pray that you would help us to reorient our lives around the story of Christ.

05:41.827 --> 05:42.708
Lord, we need you.

05:42.728 --> 05:45.152
We are desperate for you right now more than ever.

05:45.232 --> 05:49.778
And so we pray that your grace would intervene and bring change in our hearts.

05:50.434 --> 05:56.003
in our relationships, in our minds, in every aspect of our lives.

05:56.043 --> 05:58.546
So we pray this in Jesus name, amen.

06:00.930 --> 06:04.415
Well, everything in your life depends on the story that you live by.

06:04.435 --> 06:09.143
And right now, a lot of people are living by a story that goes something like this.

06:09.463 --> 06:10.865
The world is falling apart.

06:11.366 --> 06:12.528
Everything is uncertain.

06:12.828 --> 06:16.594
And there's probably no one or no thing that can make this right.

06:17.186 --> 06:20.729
But Holy Week reminds us of the true story of the world.

06:21.630 --> 06:27.076
The world, this story is that the world is broken by sin but being made new by God's grace.

06:27.596 --> 06:33.622
It's a story that says that God is at work even in the trials and catastrophes of our lives.

06:33.782 --> 06:35.944
He's at work accomplishing his purposes.

06:36.585 --> 06:39.508
And it's a story that we read of in the scriptures.

06:39.748 --> 06:45.714
It's a grand story and the Holy Week is the climax of that story.

06:46.274 --> 06:51.340
All of scripture is rushing like a raging river towards this climactic moment.

06:51.840 --> 06:56.265
All of the promises of the Old Testament are fulfilled in Christ's saving work.

06:56.766 --> 06:58.368
We believe that there is hope.

06:58.548 --> 07:03.253
It's a story that gives us hope because we know what God has done for us in Christ.

07:03.934 --> 07:07.418
And so Holy Week reminds us that we need the whole story of Jesus.

07:08.299 --> 07:11.022
Remember, it's not just good Friday and Easter.

07:11.523 --> 07:14.546
We need to see all that He has accomplished for us.

07:14.978 --> 07:22.925
Holy Week begins with Palm Sunday and the passage that I just read out of Matthew 21 is the triumphal entry of Jesus.

07:23.006 --> 07:32.775
It's where he comes into Jerusalem and this scene was one of a royal procession of Christ coming in as king declaring a kingdom.

07:32.855 --> 07:39.321
And this was a big deal because Jesus had kept his identity as the Messiah's secret.

07:40.182 --> 07:44.946
He wanted to wait for the right time to proclaim that he was king.

07:45.058 --> 07:46.460
And this was that time.

07:47.000 --> 07:48.762
And so he comes into Jerusalem.

07:48.863 --> 07:52.887
And Jerusalem is what today would be considered a small city.

07:52.907 --> 07:54.970
It's got walls going all the way around it.

07:55.571 --> 08:01.418
Historians believe that there were probably around 40,000 people that lived in Jerusalem normally.

08:01.458 --> 08:09.047
But during this week on the Passover, five to six times that many people would come to visit for this week.

08:09.067 --> 08:11.890
So you're talking over 200,000 people.

08:12.002 --> 08:14.506
tons of people there, a lot of energy.

08:14.907 --> 08:22.198
And Jesus comes in and he's being declared a king and glorified as a king.

08:22.258 --> 08:24.862
They're shouting, Hosanna, which is a praise.

08:24.882 --> 08:26.825
They're saying he's come to save us.

08:26.885 --> 08:31.272
And it leads to this question that many in the city ask, who is this?

08:32.294 --> 08:33.556
And so the answer is clear.

08:33.636 --> 08:34.898
He's a king.

08:35.234 --> 08:41.503
He rides in on a donkey, which was a common way that a king would enter into a town.

08:41.584 --> 08:45.149
He's given shouts of acclamation of his glory.

08:45.189 --> 08:53.361
They put coats and palm branches down on the ground, which in their culture was a way of laying out the red carpet.

08:54.123 --> 09:04.338
Matthew tells us that this is in fulfillment of Zechariah 9, which if you go back and read that, it's about a king who brings peace to the nations, a king whose rule extends

09:04.418 --> 09:05.820
to the ends of the earth.

09:05.980 --> 09:12.667
So clearly, Jesus is being presented here as a king, but he's a different kind of king.

09:13.248 --> 09:14.910
He's lowly and humble.

09:15.631 --> 09:23.540
He's flanked not with a battalion of soldiers, but with a ragtag group of disciples, uneducated fishermen and tax collectors.

09:25.041 --> 09:32.530
But while the difference as a kind of king, how different of a king he is, while that's hinted here,

09:32.738 --> 09:38.466
You really see that unfolding in the week to come in what is holy week.

09:38.486 --> 09:43.733
And so I want to walk through this and show us the kind of king that Jesus is.

09:43.854 --> 09:47.819
So let's jump from Palm Sunday to Maundi Thursday.

09:47.839 --> 09:52.105
And there we see that Jesus is a king who serves.

09:53.007 --> 10:01.138
Now we shouldn't be surprised by this because Jesus says earlier in his ministry in Mark 1045, the son of man did not come to be served, but to serve.

10:01.250 --> 10:03.393
and to give his life as a ransom for many.

10:04.154 --> 10:07.960
But that's on display in this last week of Jesus' life.

10:09.663 --> 10:13.348
He gathers his disciples together to celebrate the Passover meal.

10:14.009 --> 10:23.223
And if you remember the story from the Old Testament of the Exodus, it's where God delivered his people from slavery in Egypt and brought them out to the Promised Land.

10:23.864 --> 10:30.514
And the unblemished lamb was slaughtered and the blood was spread over the door to save them.

10:30.690 --> 10:33.973
this is a way that they would remember that God is their redeemer.

10:34.874 --> 10:46.445
And it would be this meal where they would go through and recount those events, but it would give them hope that God would redeem again, that there would be a new exodus, that he would save them once again.

10:46.465 --> 10:56.274
And so Jesus gathers his disciples together for the Passover meal, but in the midst of the meal, Jesus does something that's absolutely shocking.

10:56.294 --> 11:00.018
I wanna read to you out of John chapter 13,

11:00.098 --> 11:04.383
verses two through five, they're gathered together for the Passover meal.

11:04.403 --> 11:20.623
And it says this, during supper, when the devil had already put it into the heart of Judas Iscariot, Simon's son, to betray him, Jesus, knowing that the Father had given all things into his hands and that he had come from God and was going back to God, rose from the supper.

11:20.663 --> 11:26.290
He laid aside his outer garments and taking a towel, tied it around his waist.

11:26.754 --> 11:34.322
then he poured water into a basin and began to wash the disciples' feet and to wipe them with the towel that was wrapped around him.

11:35.543 --> 11:38.406
So Jesus does something that totally shocks them.

11:38.786 --> 11:43.351
Here they are sitting down and he stands up and he begins to wash their feet.

11:44.192 --> 11:49.437
Now, you need to understand that in their culture, foot washing was a common practice.

11:50.058 --> 11:53.842
They wore sandals, they spent a lot of time walking on dirt roads,

11:53.922 --> 11:55.204
And so their feet would get dirty.

11:55.244 --> 11:59.470
And so they went in, when they went into a house, it was common for their feet to be washed.

12:00.171 --> 12:05.178
But what would normally happen here is that wealthy families would have a household servant.

12:05.739 --> 12:10.646
And it was the job of the household servant to go and actually wash the feet of the guests.

12:11.668 --> 12:21.682
And so Jesus here, the king, the one who was just praised as a king, does the unthinkable and takes on the role of a servant.

12:22.050 --> 12:27.575
knowing like it says in here that God the Father has placed all things in His hand.

12:28.496 --> 12:32.460
And yet He humbles Himself and does this.

12:32.901 --> 12:34.422
I mean, think about how amazing this is.

12:34.462 --> 12:37.445
We've already seen that Jesus is powerful.

12:37.505 --> 12:38.386
He can do anything.

12:38.446 --> 12:40.468
He's already turned water to wine.

12:40.528 --> 12:41.469
He's walked on water.

12:41.509 --> 12:42.950
He brought a dead man to life.

12:43.611 --> 12:47.495
He could have snapped his fingers and their feet would have been clean.

12:48.416 --> 12:50.898
But no, He was showing him something beautiful here.

12:51.458 --> 12:55.704
by getting down and scrubbing their feet one at a time.

12:56.705 --> 13:02.613
It must have taken a long time for him to go around the table to all 12 disciples washing their feet.

13:03.694 --> 13:07.138
But there was one man who caused Jesus to pause.

13:07.439 --> 13:10.403
Peter's response is noted in verse six.

13:10.943 --> 13:11.905
And listen to what it says.

13:11.925 --> 13:17.392
It says, Jesus came to Simon Peter who said to him, Lord, do you wash my feet?

13:18.153 --> 13:19.154
Jesus answered him.

13:19.554 --> 13:23.781
What I am doing, you do not understand now, but afterward you will understand."

13:24.482 --> 13:27.066
Peter said to him, you shall never wash my feet.

13:27.747 --> 13:32.454
Jesus answered him, if I do not wash you, you have no share with me.

13:33.736 --> 13:39.986
Now, Jesus is washing everyone's feet and Peter stops him and says, no, you shouldn't wash my feet.

13:41.228 --> 13:43.652
He wouldn't receive from Jesus.

13:44.653 --> 13:47.698
And I think that many of us, I certainly do,

13:47.778 --> 13:50.161
We have a hard time receiving.

13:51.122 --> 13:51.883
And why is that?

13:51.923 --> 13:53.785
Why do we have a hard time receiving from others?

13:53.865 --> 13:57.470
Because well, if we receive, then we can't take credit for it.

13:57.510 --> 14:08.764
Maybe it implies that I need help, especially in a culture where we associate strength with independence to receive from others means I must be weak.

14:08.784 --> 14:13.810
But no, Jesus says to Peter, unless I wash you, you have no share with me.

14:14.786 --> 14:19.873
And so I want you to understand that Jesus is the king who comes to us as a servant as well.

14:20.734 --> 14:25.081
He comes to wash our feet, to serve us even.

14:25.822 --> 14:31.530
I want you to know this, that Jesus is gracious to you, whether you like it or not.

14:31.770 --> 14:33.212
He is gracious to you.

14:33.232 --> 14:36.957
The question is, will you receive or resist of his grace?

14:37.959 --> 14:41.444
He says to you, unless I wash you, you have no part of me.

14:42.044 --> 14:43.186
So the question is,

14:43.554 --> 14:46.478
Will you let Jesus wash you?

14:47.659 --> 14:55.609
See this beautiful, beautiful scene of a royal king getting down and washing his disciples' feet.

14:56.610 --> 15:01.296
And this happens on what is traditionally known as Maundi Thursday.

15:01.476 --> 15:03.058
Now the word Maundi is a little strange.

15:03.158 --> 15:08.505
I remember being a kid and hearing that and I thought somebody said Monday Thursday and I thought that doesn't make sense at all.

15:09.006 --> 15:12.530
But it's Maundi Thursday and that word Maundi comes from a Latin word

15:13.058 --> 15:14.300
That means commandment.

15:15.101 --> 15:25.435
And that comes from John 13, 34, where after Jesus washes his disciples' feet, he says this, a new commandment I give to you that you love one another.

15:26.176 --> 15:30.802
Just as I have loved you, you also are to love one another.

15:31.903 --> 15:39.253
So what we have here is not only a picture of Christ, this king who serves, but we have the kind of culture that the church is supposed to be.

15:39.273 --> 15:42.738
People who lay down the rights for one another.

15:43.266 --> 15:46.790
people who serve one another, people who love one another.

15:47.311 --> 15:52.077
When we recognize how Christ has served us, then that makes us a people of service with one another.

15:52.818 --> 15:56.222
So we learn in this holy week that Jesus is a king who serves.

15:56.623 --> 15:59.627
Secondly, we learn that he's a king who suffers.

16:00.508 --> 16:01.870
And this is shocking.

16:01.910 --> 16:04.954
I mean, talk about defying expectations for what a king is.

16:05.775 --> 16:07.797
What king willingly suffers?

16:08.178 --> 16:11.602
No, a king would have others suffer so that he wouldn't have to.

16:11.682 --> 16:14.686
And yet we're going to see that Jesus is a king who suffers.

16:15.427 --> 16:21.454
And this is especially relevant to us right now because there's just a lot of suffering right now in our city and in our world.

16:22.275 --> 16:29.543
And listen, if you're thinking about this pandemic, mostly in terms of inconvenience, then you're approaching it the wrong way.

16:30.124 --> 16:31.886
This is not about inconvenience.

16:31.966 --> 16:33.729
It's about suffering.

16:33.749 --> 16:34.830
Thousands have died.

16:35.070 --> 16:36.592
Millions of people are sick.

16:36.932 --> 16:38.715
Many more are vulnerable.

16:39.075 --> 16:41.618
There is so much suffering right now.

16:42.274 --> 16:47.784
But what we learn from Holy Week is that Christ has entered into that suffering.

16:47.804 --> 16:53.255
Jesus is, as Isaiah 53 says, a man of sorrows acquainted with grief.

16:54.116 --> 17:01.971
Hebrews 2, 18 says, because he himself has suffered when he was tempted, he is able to help those who are being tempted.

17:03.334 --> 17:05.618
Jesus is a king who suffered.

17:06.082 --> 17:15.412
And we'll talk about physical pain in a little bit when we get to the cross, but here I actually want to focus more on the internal emotional suffering that Jesus went through.

17:15.452 --> 17:23.641
When Jesus came into Jerusalem on that last week, we're told in Luke 19 that Jesus wept over the city.

17:24.522 --> 17:27.505
He looked at the city and he was so moved that he wept.

17:28.306 --> 17:35.474
In Matthew 23 verse 37, Jesus looking over the city of Jerusalem says this,

17:35.586 --> 17:41.191
Oh, Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to it.

17:41.712 --> 17:48.738
How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings and you were not willing?

17:49.819 --> 17:53.463
Jesus looks over the city and he says, I have mercy on you, but you're not willing.

17:53.483 --> 18:02.511
I think that if Jesus came in the flesh to Los Angeles and looked over the city, I think he would weep.

18:03.953 --> 18:05.234
When he saw the suffering,

18:05.858 --> 18:22.274
the sickness, when he saw the loss, when he saw how even what's happening now is making the most vulnerable people in our city even more vulnerable, that there's more people in the streets, there's more people who are going hungry.

18:23.335 --> 18:29.922
And I think Jesus would look over Los Angeles and weep, but not just for seeing the state of the suffering.

18:30.362 --> 18:34.226
I think he would also weep because he is offering grace and people are ignoring him.

18:35.138 --> 18:38.823
He's saying, I'm holding out my hands, but you will not come.

18:40.165 --> 18:50.660
And so we see Jesus weeping over the city, but we're told right after he washes his disciples' feet that he goes to a garden called Gethsemane.

18:51.140 --> 18:58.791
And I want to read this to you out of Matthew chapter 26, where it tells us the story of Jesus in the garden of Gethsemane.

18:58.871 --> 19:03.698
Matthew 26, in verses 36 through 39, it says,

19:04.290 --> 19:11.077
Then Jesus went with them to a place called Gethsemane, and he said to his disciples, sit here while I go over there and pray.

19:11.838 --> 19:16.763
And taking with him Peter and the two sons of Zebedee, he began to be sorrowful and troubled.

19:17.624 --> 19:23.811
Then he said to them, my soul is very sorrowful, even to death, remain here and watch with me.

19:24.592 --> 19:34.162
And going a little farther, he fell on his face and prayed, saying, my father, if it is possible, let this cup pass from me, nevertheless, not as I will,

19:34.562 --> 19:35.263
but as you will.

19:36.164 --> 19:38.668
You see Jesus here suffering immensely.

19:38.748 --> 19:39.630
He's troubled.

19:40.010 --> 19:41.472
He's sorrowful.

19:43.215 --> 19:47.261
We're told elsewhere that he's sweating drops of blood.

19:48.983 --> 19:56.114
My wife and I went to Jerusalem years ago and we were able to go to the Garden of Gethsemane.

19:56.642 --> 20:04.570
And it's one of the places where historians are rather certain that this is actually right where Jesus was in this time.

20:04.590 --> 20:09.614
It's on the Mount of Olives and they have these really old olive trees.

20:09.674 --> 20:21.666
And I remember being there and being told about them, some of them they think are over 2,000 years old, which means they would have been the same trees that I was looking at there in Jerusalem that Jesus was by praying under during this time.

20:22.547 --> 20:25.970
And being there and looking over the Garden of Gethsemane

20:26.370 --> 20:37.507
Having my feet on that same ground, looking back over the city of Jerusalem with the same view that he would have had, it made me realize how real this whole thing was.

20:38.168 --> 20:41.454
This wasn't just a story, some fairy tale.

20:42.295 --> 20:54.514
Jesus was there, fully human, filled with sorrow and grief, weeping, crying out to the Father, and yet submitting.

20:55.394 --> 21:00.300
following the plan all along saying, not my will, but your will be done.

21:01.542 --> 21:04.806
Jesus is no stranger to pain and sorrow.

21:05.427 --> 21:08.832
He's a king who serves and he's a king who suffers.

21:09.893 --> 21:15.360
But while we've seen both of those, the third thing that we need to see from the Holy because that Jesus is a king who saves.

21:16.361 --> 21:17.323
And think about it like this.

21:18.584 --> 21:22.930
On Palm Sunday, Jesus came in and he was

21:23.458 --> 21:25.662
He was adorned by this crowd.

21:25.742 --> 21:27.946
They're crying out to him as a great king.

21:28.006 --> 21:30.310
They're praising him, Hosanna.

21:31.612 --> 21:35.178
But from Sunday, everything changes by the time we get to Friday.

21:35.979 --> 21:41.769
The shouts of praise from the crowd turned into shouts from a mob saying, crucify him.

21:42.991 --> 21:47.058
See, Jesus was a different kind of king than they expected and they didn't like it.

21:47.682 --> 21:49.264
They didn't want a king who served.

21:49.324 --> 21:51.166
They didn't want a king who suffered.

21:51.207 --> 21:56.393
They wanted a king who had come and ruled by force and set up a political kingdom right there.

21:56.453 --> 21:58.676
And so they killed him.

21:59.197 --> 22:00.198
They put him on a cross.

22:01.560 --> 22:07.187
But I want you to know that it's not just their shouts and their sin that put Jesus on the cross.

22:07.888 --> 22:10.471
It was our sin that led Christ to the cross.

22:11.452 --> 22:12.754
John Stott says,

22:12.834 --> 22:19.442
Before we can begin to see the cross as something done for us, we have to see it as something done by us.

22:20.624 --> 22:24.048
We've all sinned and fallen short of the glory of God.

22:24.729 --> 22:28.673
And it's our sin, our rebellion against God, our choosing our own way.

22:29.054 --> 22:35.562
That's the very reason that Christ went to the cross to pay for our sin, to reconcile us to God.

22:36.363 --> 22:38.866
But this is all connected to what we saw earlier.

22:39.298 --> 22:43.285
and the triumphal entry where Jesus comes as a king, bringing a kingdom.

22:43.325 --> 22:51.298
And remember, a kingdom isn't, that of course doesn't just mean that Jesus kind of gets a little religious compartment of your life.

22:52.119 --> 22:56.065
Now it means he reigns over all of life and over all of creation.

22:57.187 --> 23:06.162
And I love at the end of Mark, how when Mark tells of the crucifixion of Christ, the kingdom imagery is really strong throughout the whole story.

23:06.594 --> 23:08.316
Jesus is mocked as a king.

23:08.356 --> 23:10.019
He's wearing a crown of thorns.

23:10.039 --> 23:12.642
He's got a sign over his head that says, King of the Jews.

23:13.463 --> 23:16.347
And he's on the cross and everyone's mocking him.

23:16.407 --> 23:21.735
And they say to him in verse 30 of Mark 15, save yourself and come down from the cross.

23:22.876 --> 23:25.700
But Jesus didn't come down from the cross to save himself.

23:26.381 --> 23:28.724
He stayed on the cross to save us.

23:30.146 --> 23:35.794
See, he was showing his power, but he was showing that his power is controlled by love.

23:36.322 --> 23:41.388
He was showing that he truly is a king, but he reigns with mercy and grace.

23:42.129 --> 23:48.638
He stayed on the cross out of sovereign love for us that we might be forgiven.

23:48.678 --> 23:50.260
He's our substitute.

23:50.640 --> 23:52.963
We deserve to pay the penalty for our own sins.

23:53.103 --> 23:55.686
And Christ took that in our place.

23:56.688 --> 24:04.818
That's why in Colossians 1 verse 21, it says, you who are once alienated and hostile in mind, doing evil deeds,

24:05.186 --> 24:14.919
He has now reconciled in his body of flesh by his death in order to present you holy and blameless and above reproach before him.

24:14.959 --> 24:22.469
Because of what Christ has done on the cross, we're declared righteous, holy, blameless, we're reconciled to God.

24:23.431 --> 24:34.866
That's why Friday, a day that was a day of execution and death is actually known as good Friday because it's God's way of saving us by His grace.

24:35.650 --> 24:45.407
So when we step back and think about everything that we're experiencing in our world right now, a lot of people would ask the question, where is God in the midst of suffering?

24:46.248 --> 24:49.434
Where is God in the midst of everything that's happening with COVID-19?

24:49.454 --> 24:54.022
Well, the answer that we learned from the scriptures is that he's with us.

24:54.743 --> 24:56.306
He's the God of the cross.

24:56.738 --> 24:58.680
He is not far from our suffering.

24:58.760 --> 25:00.722
He is not distant from our pain.

25:01.163 --> 25:06.789
He has entered into the brokenness and suffering of this world and sending his son, Jesus Christ.

25:07.850 --> 25:13.336
And I want you to know that not only is God here with us in this, but God is in your pain.

25:13.416 --> 25:14.737
God is in your suffering.

25:14.757 --> 25:17.280
He has entered into the brokenness in your life.

25:18.221 --> 25:26.610
I know that so many people in our church, so many people in our city are suffering in different ways, physically, financially, socially, relationally, all of it.

25:27.522 --> 25:32.387
We believe in the God of the cross who enters into our suffering and is with us.

25:33.809 --> 25:38.514
A lot of people ask the question, well, if God is real, what's he going to do about the coronavirus?

25:38.534 --> 25:40.096
Is God going to do anything?

25:40.136 --> 25:44.881
What we learn from the scriptures is that he's already done the greatest thing.

25:45.682 --> 25:50.727
He sent his son to enter in to the brokenness, to die for our sins.

25:52.309 --> 25:57.234
So we certainly have to trust in God's timing and in his plan.

25:57.858 --> 26:00.884
But we can know that God is with us and our suffering.

26:01.264 --> 26:03.388
He transforms us through suffering.

26:03.408 --> 26:06.755
And one day he will put an end to all suffering.

26:08.097 --> 26:13.868
In John 1633, Jesus said, in this world, you will have trouble, but take heart.

26:14.369 --> 26:15.471
I have overcome the world.

26:16.673 --> 26:18.336
So he told us it's not going to be easy.

26:19.218 --> 26:21.362
There is going to be trial and hardship.

26:21.826 --> 26:26.932
But Christ is with us in that, bringing healing and redemption and forgiveness and freedom.

26:27.273 --> 26:31.018
And that is available to us today by trusting in Christ.

26:32.760 --> 26:38.227
Now, we've talked about Palm Sunday and Monday, Thursday and Good Friday.

26:39.989 --> 26:41.751
But a lot of people forget about Saturday.

26:42.472 --> 26:45.416
You've got Good Friday, you've got Easter Sunday, but what about Saturday?

26:46.297 --> 26:50.482
Well, traditionally it's known as Holy Saturday.

26:50.818 --> 26:54.623
It's overlooked, but I think it's really important for us, especially now.

26:55.304 --> 27:02.413
And there's a lot of debates about where Jesus was and what he was doing on that day in between Friday and Sunday.

27:02.473 --> 27:04.055
That's for another time.

27:04.636 --> 27:11.905
But what I want to acknowledge now is Holy Saturday gets at the tension between crucifixion and resurrection.

27:12.666 --> 27:15.009
It's a tension that defines the Christian life.

27:16.191 --> 27:18.514
The Apostle Paul says in Galatians 2.20,

27:18.594 --> 27:23.219
I've been crucified with Christ and is no longer I who live, but Christ who lives in me.

27:23.279 --> 27:29.847
And so Holy Saturday teaches us to embrace the tension between good Friday and Easter Sunday.

27:30.628 --> 27:37.396
We follow a crucified and resurrected savior who brought the victory of the kingdom through suffering and service.

27:38.137 --> 27:43.623
And so this week, Holy Week, it's a time for us to embrace that very tension.

27:44.224 --> 27:46.226
We lament and we celebrate.

27:46.562 --> 27:47.884
We cry and we sing.

27:47.924 --> 27:49.806
We wait and we work.

27:50.187 --> 28:00.440
And through it all, we keep our eyes fixed on Jesus, knowing that though we wait in silence, though we are patient in the dark, that Easter is coming.

28:01.021 --> 28:01.482
Let's pray.

28:04.025 --> 28:07.910
God, we thank you that you're with us in hard times.

28:09.693 --> 28:13.778
I pray, Lord, that when we doubt that, that you would remind us of the cross.

28:15.202 --> 28:18.867
that our king has come, and he has come as a servant.

28:20.289 --> 28:27.278
He has come as one who is willing to suffer in our place for our sins, and he has come as one who saves.

28:28.440 --> 28:30.583
God, we need you to save us.

28:31.944 --> 28:45.202
God, I pray for anyone right now who's listening to this, who can hear my voice and who doesn't know you as Lord and Savior, would you give them the faith to cry out, save me, to be able to entrust their lives to you knowing,

28:45.442 --> 28:47.524
that you're a good and righteous King.

28:49.426 --> 29:06.786
God, we pray that you would give us the perspective of faith in everything that's happening in our city and in our world right now, that we would trust that you are accomplishing your purposes, that you are at work, that you are bringing renewal amidst the brokenness.

29:08.067 --> 29:13.874
God, would you fill us with your spirit to be able to be a people of hope, a people of peace,

29:14.274 --> 29:18.775
even a people of joy in the midst of this suffering because we know that you are with us.

29:19.378 --> 29:21.970
We pray this in Jesus name, amen.

